How is Curley's wife presented in Of Mice and Men?  
You must use the context of the novel in your answer.

Ostensibly, Curley's wife is an extremely complex character. She is presented as flirtatious and seeks attention from the rest of the ranch, yet is lonely, isolated from others and is disadvantaged for being a woman. Steinbeck shows the depressing role of women during the 1930s, through the character of Curley's wife.

The setting of Of Mice and Men during 1930s America is important as women at the time were percieved as inferior to men, and their role in life was percieved to be obtaining a husband which would support them. This meant that women's roles were largely percieved to be supportive to men, reflected in the way that women were normally only allowed household roles. 

This is reflected in Curley's wife's name, as she doesn't have a name, reflecting her objectification within the ranch. Curley himself reveals this when Candy refers to his "glove fulla' Vaseline," appearingly using this to highlight his superiority through having a wife (as the other characters do not). Yet, this is an extremely vulgar displayal as Curley is using his wife as a show of his apparent sexual prowess.

In addition to being objectified, Curley's wife also has a loveless relationship with Curley. This is seen as Curley and his wife are never seen together in the novella except her death, always "looking" for each other. In addition, Curley also goes to the "cathouse" even after their marriage, disregarding their relationship. Steinbeck uses the distance between the two to reinforce Curley's wife's powerless position as she is insatisifed yet is dependent with her own husband. 

Curley's wife's only power is her appearance, in which she uses to attempt to get attention from the other men. A long description is used during her introduction, focusing on her appearance, for example with her "rouged lips." She also wears an abundance of red clothing, which symbolically is linked to sex, love and lust. It garners attention from the other men, as Lennie "stares" at her causing her to "bridle." 

Yet, Curley's wife is percieved as promiscuous from the other men. The other ranch men avoid her, describing her using derogatory terms, as George calls her a "rat-trap" and "jail bait." Yet, most of these men hold double standards as most of their interactions with women stem from going to the "cathouse" where they meet prostitutes. Their perception of women as promiscious stem from their flawed perception of women as objects of sex.  Curley's wife is never invited nor accepted by the other men, as she is described as "looking in," symbolising how she is always looking into the workers' lives but is isolated and not part of their community. She is only ever greeted/respected by Slim, who greets her with "Hi, good-lookin." Curley's wife is isolated and is percieved as promiscuous by men holding double-standards.

This isolation is shown to have pervading effects on Curley's wife. She is shown to exert this frustration out on Lennie, as she questions "Why can't I talk to nobody? I get awful lonely." When she speaks to Lennie, she also "tumbles out in a passion of communication," suggesting how she is pouring out her thoughts and feelings over years, highlighting her loneliness and isolation. Contrasted with her seemingly promiscuity and percieved danger, this generates empathy from the reader, perhaps used by Steinbeck to critique the sexism present within 1930s America.

This empathy is further emphasised by the nature symbolism during the first and last chapters of the novella. The "water snake" is usually mistaken as dangerous and venomous, yet is actually harmless. In addition, it is also eaten by a "heron" during the last chapter, symbolising how Curley's wife is percieved as dangerous and avoided by the men, and easily killed by Lennie. In addition to this, a new water snake comes out after the first water snake's death, as if suggesting that Curley's wife is easily replaceable.

#### **How is Curley‚Äôs wife presented in Of Mice and Men?** {#how-is-curley‚Äôs-wife-presented-in-of-mice-and-men?}

Discuss the character of Curley's wife in the novel.

You must consider the context of the novel in your answer.

Plan:  
\- promiscuous  
\- isolated  
\- only acknowledged by Slim  
\- lonely   
\- neglected  
\- dreamer

Curley's wife is an incredibly complex character in Of Mice and Men. Being the only female on the ranch, she is initially presented as promiscuous and isolated, only acknowledged by Slim. However, as the novella progresses, we see how Curley's wife is neglected, lonely, and had failed dreams, emphasising her multi-faceted character.

Curley's wife is presented as promiscous and objectified as she is initially introduced by the other men. From her name alone, it symbolises how she is presented and treated without an identity, as women who married at the time were meant to be subordinate to men. She is introduced by Candy, calling her a "tramp," showing how women were believed to be promiscuous and judged immediately by their gender at the time. The only important thing about the women at the time, is if they were "Purty?" as George asks, showing how women were judged by their appearance and thus were treated worse than men. Her promiscuity is accentuated as Steinbeck gives Curley's wife the largest character description, with "full, rouged lips" and the colour of "red" on her clothing, symbolising love, lust and promiscuity. Unlike the other characters, she is the only character who is only initially described through her appearance, highlighting how through Steinbeck's or society's viewpoint of women were completely judged by their appearance. Curley's wife is also presented as dangerous just because of her appearance and promiscuity as he warns Lennie of how she is a "rattrap," showing how women were accused of their own flirtatious behaviour despite it being the only factor that gains the men's attention, reflected through George and the other men's misogynistic views towards women. With all of the men all going to "Susy's place," or the brothel in the weekends, it only reinforces the men's misogyny and objectification of women as migrant workers could not afford to have relationships and marriages, and thus would only meet and treat women as commodities as though they were prostitutes.

However, Curley's wife is also isolated by all the other men in the novella, as they refuse to talk to her, seeing her as a risk due to being Curley's wife, and thus believe that they may get in trouble with Curley. This is reflected through Curley's insecure nature, continually asking "seen my wife?" highlighting his posessive and insecure nature regarding his wife. Because of this, the characters always refuse to speak to her, and thus she is forced to begin "looking in\[to\]" their conversations, as the men treat her as a dangerous "jailbait" that could get them in jail due to Curley's position as the Boss's son and Curley's innate insecurity. In addition, Curley's wife is also presented as isolated and ignored by Curley himself, as he is always physically distant from Curley and never are together in the same chapter together, apart from Curley's wife's death, symbolising how Curley's wife lives a loveless and lonely marriage. This is further reinforced as Curley himself objectifies and uses Curley's wife as a metaphorical trophy \-- he has a "glove fulla' Vaseline" \-- showing how Curley uses his wife as a show for his insecurity,  attempting to demonstrate that he has sexual prowess but ironically highlighting his insecurity and suggesting he is impotent, and reflecting the ideas of masculinity at the time as men being the dominant individual in the marriage as a whole. Curley's wife's isolation from Curley is so blatant that they believe Curley's wife will "clear out for twenty bucks," not only appling their misogynistic views but also showing how women were viewed as commodities as they believe their wealth alone could control women.

However, Curley's wife is also presented to be lonely and neglected, showing how women were completely misunderstood in 1930s society and how they are truly human at heart. This is shown through how Curley's wife opens up to Lennie, where she "tumbled out in a passion of communication," showing how she has no one to talk to, not the ranch workers nor Curley, and it shows how her thoughts have been bottled inward and thus provides a emotional side to her character which has not been explored before, and as this only happens at near the end of the novella, alone in the barn it symbolises how men were put in front of women in terms of work, respect and status reflective of the patriarchal society at the time. In addition, she opens up to Lennie, a mentally disabled character who only cares about "tend\[ing\] the rabbits," and thus being unable to understand barely anything she says. Despite this, she desires to communicate and understand him, offering him to touch her hair to garner his interest, showing how desperate she is for communication within the ranch where the men completely ignore, disrespect and do not acknolwedge her as a person. 

Curley's wife is also presented to be let down by the patriarchal society as she is completely reliant on men to achieve her dreams. She describes her dream where she "could've been in the movies," reflecting how women at the time had impossible ideals of beauty and contributing to the patriarchal society seen in 1930s then. However, she is shown to be reliant on the men for her dreams: she says how "a man" told her she "could've been in the pitchers," showing how women like Curley's wife at the time could not achieve positions of power given that jobs were favoured to men than women at the time, and women were paid less thn men at the time \-- reflected in how Curley's wife in the end never got her dream of acting, as the other men abuse their status and power to manipulate women such as Curley's wife in this instance for their own desires. This is further seen through Curley's wife's marriage with Curley: they met on the same day, and Curley's wife is jobless and is expected to stay inside Curley's home against her wishes. She even hates her marriage, stating that "Curley ain't a nice fella," showing how she is forced to stay in the marriage as he relies on Curley for economic support as she is not allowed to get a job, the norm for married women at the time in the Great Depression. She is ultimately let down by the ideal of the American Dream: where anyone can live a life that is "better, richer, and fuller for everyone," \-- her dreams and ambitions are clearly impossible for Curley's wife due to her gender. 

\+ Curley's wife's death and how Curley ignores it

Curley's wife is thus presented, as a result of these factors, to be a complex character in Of Mice and Men. She is objectified, isolated due to the patriarchal society at the time, yet Steinbeck presents her as a victim of such society by also presenting her as lonely, neglected and reliant on men. Being the only prominent character who exists and dies in the novella, Steinbeck presents how Curley's wife and women lived in a society which does not accept women as a whole.

#### **Exemplar** {#exemplar}

AO1, AO2

Eva Smith is presented as a x that was y because of z  
Eva Smith is presented as x when y  
Intro  
In this whodunnit play, Priestley aims to evoke sympathy for the pivotal character Eva Smith, though never seen at all in the play.

P1: Eva‚Äôs cruel suffering  
Upon the arrival of Inspector Goole, Priestley presents Eva as a character who went through various accounts of suffering while still alive on Earth.

Evidence: The Inspector mentions ‚Äúshe‚Äôd swallowed a lot of strong disinfectant‚Äù and ‚Äúburnt her inside out.‚Äù  
Analysis 1: The adjective ‚Äústrong‚Äù used to qualify the disinfectant reveals to the audience that if Eva needed a liquid so strong, the weight and gravity of her suffering was also strong, which they later realise in the play.  
Analysis 2: Similarly, Priestley‚Äôs use of the deep emotive phrase, ‚Äúburnt her inside out‚Äù could be parallel to the allusion of hell, which causes ‚Äúburning of souls and gnashing of teeth.‚Äù   
Audience Effect 1: This hellish description of the utter pain Eva Smith went through just to escape life, allows the audience to sympathise with her as they start to realise, or already know, the ‚Äúhell‚Äù she faced in real life.   
Audience Effect 2: Priestley uses this as a way to give the 1945 audience an idea of the mistreatment of the working class in 1912 that will make them resort in the worst choice of suicide.

P2 \- Prejudice against women  
Furthermore, along the play, Eva Smith is presented as a suffragette\* that was prejudiced because of her gender.  
Evidence 1: During the interrogation of Mr. Birling, the audience finds out that Eva Smith was ‚Äúdischarged‚Äù out of Birlings and Co. because she opted for higher pay and paved the way for a strike.  
Analysis 1: The strong imperative choice of word ‚Äúdischarged‚Äù used by Mr. Birling presents the inhumane treatment of Eva Smith, and of working class people at the time.   
Audience Effect 1: He sent her off like she was nothing, making me and the audience sympathise with Eva Smith at the indubitable harshness towards women like her.  
Evidence 2: Similarly, even after Mr. Birling knows about Eva‚Äôs suicide, he still describes her as ‚Äúwretched‚Äù showing no empathy or remorse towards his actions.  
Audience Effect 2: Priestley also uses this to highlight the ignorance of the capitalist society in 1912 to the working class, which boils up hatred to capitalist like Mr Birling as he shows no diplomacy to a sensitive issue as suicide, further paralleling the treatment torwards the character of Eva Smith; no case at all.

P4 \- Vulnerable to social hierarchy  
Priestley also presents the character of Eva Smith as being inevitably vulnerable to the social hierarchy in the Edwardian period.  
Evidence 1: We learn that Sheila orders the manager of Milwards ‚Äúto get rid of the girl‚Äù and use her capitalist power to persuade them or ‚Äúclose our accounts with them.‚Äù  
Explain 1: Just after being fired from Birlings and Co., Eva took up another job at MIlwards which she is quickly fired from due to the (Point 1:) jealousy of Sheila Birling.  
Analysis 1: She uses imperatives like ‚Äúget rid‚Äù which emphasises the unlimited power Sheila has as a member of the upper-middle class citizens, as she is able to convince the manager by threatening to ‚Äúclose accounts‚Äù showing the exploitation of power in the capitalist society to the vulnerable working class.  
Explain 2: Eva Smith is a victim of this exploitation as she cannot even voice her opinion as she is too little in the big capitalist and powerful world,

**intro**  
Ostensibly, the Inspector is presented as a powerful character. His purpose is outlined in the title of the play ‚ÄúAn Inspector Calls,‚Äù as he swiftly begins ‚Äúcutting in,‚Äù interrogating the Birling family (and Gerald Croft) about the murder of Eva Smith. However, as the play develops, it is clear that his uncanny knowledge about the family, his speech, and his sudden disappearance indicate his purpose to be beyond the events of Eva‚Äôs death itself, and instead as a warning against capitalism.

**The Inspector as a disruptive and powerful force**

- ‚Äúsharp‚Äù ringing of the doorbell  
  - irruptive entrance, butting in  
- ‚Äúpink and intimate‚Äù \-\> ‚Äúbrighter and harder‚Äù  
  - emblematic of metaphorical function  
- ‚Äúcreates at once an impression of massiveness, solidity and purposefulness‚Äù  
  - ‚Äúsolidity,‚Äù unmoveable, status of Birlings are powerless  
- ‚Äúbut the Inspector imposes himself between them and the photograph‚Äù  
  - physically taking control of the investigation, placing his body between the photograph and the higher class men  
- ‚ÄúI ought to warn you that he‚Äôs an old friend of mine‚Ä¶we play golf together‚Äù ‚Äú(dryly) I don‚Äôt play golf‚Äù  
  - simple and flippant (shallow) comment  
  - shows power the Inspector wields, as a voice of the common people  
  - willing to stand against those who believe their position gives them special treatment

**The Inspector as a quasi-supernatural figure, with an uncanny knowledge about the family**

- obvious pun ‚Äúghoul‚Äù  
  - plays on idea of how he appears to be a quasi-supernatural being, haunting the Birling family  
- uncanny knowledge of every aspect of the events which resulted in the tragic death of Eva Smith	  
  - set him up as something more than a natural police Inspector  
- Yet it is the very ending of the play that is the most strange ‚Äì not a member of the Brumley police force  
  - Crucially, only Eric and Sheila realise his significance ‚Äì Sheila says ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs important‚Äù is ‚Äúnot whether a man is a police inspector or not‚Äù but what they did to Eva Smith. Eric says ‚Äúhe was our police inspector all right‚Äù  
- Sheila says he was ‚Äúfrightening‚Äù and that ‚Äúhe inspected us all right.‚Äù   
- rhetoric at Act 3 echoes Inspector‚Äôs final speech: she talks about how she ‚Äúremember\[s\]‚Äù and the ‚Äúfire and blood and anguish‚Äù

**The Inspector as Priestley‚Äôs voice in the play**

- After showing how each of the Birlings and Gerald are implicated in Eva Smith‚Äôs suicide, the Inspector ends with a final speech.  
- ‚ÄúThere are millions and millions and millions of Eva Smiths and John Smiths left with us, with their lives, their hopes and fears, their suffering and chance of happiness, all intertwined with our lives‚Äù.  
  - repetition of ‚Äúmillions‚Äù  
  - plays on the commonality of the last name ‚ÄúSmith‚Äù and common first names, symbolic of society as a whole  
- Apocalyptic imagery ‚ÄúIf men will not learn that lesson, then they will be taught it in blood and fire and anguish‚Äù  
  - is emotive and evocative, given obvious reference to two world wars  
  - yet what is quite subversive about Priestley‚Äôs message here is the suggestion that violence and horror of thte first half of the wars was somehow linked to the selfishness of individuals and a lack of empathy  
- ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt live alone. We are members of one body. We are responsible for each other.‚Äù  
  - Anaphora ‚ÄúWe‚Äù and declaratives and tricolon draw attention of audience as a conclusive statement  
  - metaphor ‚Äúmembers of one body‚Äù   
  - suggests that like limbs of a body we cannot survive without each other again emphasising the socialist idea that we must look out for the most vulnerable in society  
- indicated by the final ring of the telephone before the curtain fall  
  - the final punishment of the Inspector on the Birlings as the older Birlings and Gerald do not change their capitalist views. Perhaps alluding to the first or second world war.

**conc**  
Priestley therefore presents the Inspector as powerful voice for the lower-class, and his purpose as the near-supernatural surrogate author for Priestley‚Äôs socialist and equalitarian views.

Intro: **Context of theme**  
*Priestley‚Äôs opinion on the theme, and how that may look in the modern audience.*

- Priestley believes that capitalism is immoral and socialism is moral.   
- Capitalism creates the class structures, where the more wealthy you are, the more privileged your life becomes.

Point 1: Mrs Birling & Eva Smith \- contempt for lower-class  
*Intro: mention the theme; Outro: connect with next paragraph* 

- The interactions between Mrs Birling and Eva Smith show the significance of class in determining their life.

- ‚ÄúShe was claiming elaborate fine feelings ‚Ä¶. that were simply absurd for a girl in her position.‚Äù ‚Üí verb ‚Äúclaiming‚Äù suggests falsehood, reasoning ‚Äúher position,‚Äù determiner for how she could even feel. ‚Äúabsurd‚Äù denotes impossibility.   
- ‚ÄúAs a girl of that sort would ever refuse money\!‚Äù Exclamatory, determiner ‚Äúthat‚Äù create defamatory and snobbish tone. Adverb ‚Äúever,‚Äù impossibility. Referral to Eva as ‚Äúa girl,‚Äù not acknowledging her as an individual. 

- Mrs Birling‚Äôs contempt with the lower class seem rooted in privilege and her upper-ground background, as she may be brought up to have a warped perception of the lower class.

Point 2: Mr Birling \- abuse of lower-class  
*Intro: mention the theme; Outro: connect with next paragraph* 

- Mr Birling, despite working tremendously to reach the middle-class, takes full advantage of the lower class.

- ‚Äúthat wretched girl‚Äôs suicide‚Äù ‚Üí determiner ‚Äúthat,‚Äù distant and critiquing ‚Äúwretched‚Äù derogatory and impersonal terms.  
- ‚Äúit‚Äôs my duty to keep labour costs down‚Äù ‚Üí greater importance to his ‚Äúlabour costs‚Äù instead of his own workers, very monetary focused. Idea of lowering wellbeing of lower-class as his ‚Äúduty,‚Äù no sense of responsibility for healthy or well-paid workers.  
- ‚Äúthey‚Äôd soon be asking for the earth‚Äù ‚Üí 

- Mr Birling‚Äôs resounding belief in capitalism is shown to guide his actions; he believes it brings him success. Priestley suggests being higher on the class ladder means being more capitalist and immoral.

Point 3: Gerald \- upper-class, conscious immorality  
*Intro: mention the theme; Outro: connect with next paragraph* 

- Gerald shows how his upper-class status define him despite being young generation.

- ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre respectable citizens and not criminals‚Äù irony, every character has done something immoral to Eva Smith. Classist, implying that only the ‚Äúnon-respectable‚Äù citizens, lower-class, are capable of being criminals.   
- ‚ÄúI‚Äôm rather more ‚Äì upset ‚Äì by this business than I probably appear to be,‚Äù **em dashes** show remorse, **noun ‚Äúbusiness‚Äù** suggests otherwise, ironic: he goes to verify the inspector‚Äôs identity ‚Üí lying shows he knows he is in the wrong  
- ‚ÄúEverything's all right now. What about this ring?‚Äù Uses the ring as an allure

- Gerald consciously abuses his upper-class to excuse his immoral actions. Priestley shows how the young generation criminalising the old is not enough: capitalism and the class system must change.

Conclusion  
*Priestley‚Äôs intentions with the theme, differing audience responses, how should we respond, final answer of question.*

- Priestley implements the class structure to highlight the immoral categorization of people by wealth and status.  
- He suggests that society will not change (just like the Birlings) until the younger generation steps up, in favour of socialism.

(30)

Eric is presented as a troubled young man within the Birlings family, yet is also positioned to change and grow. Seen through his stage description as "half shy, half assertive," we can see how his viewpoint is not rigid and contrasts the older Birlings. As the play progresses, he becomes more assertive and compassionate, as he learns from his mistakes and takse the Inspector's words to heart.

Eric's troublesomeness is displayed during Act 1 as he is presented as drunk and disrespectful. He is shown to continually interrupt the family with "rather noisily" outbursts such as "Steady the Buffs\!" and "suddenly guffaws," cutting off the conversation between Gerald and Sheila.  His drunkness, otherwise referred to as being "squiffy," presents him as initially unreliable and lazy, in addition to the insults such as being an "ass" in the celebration. 

**Eric‚Äôs response when the Inspector questions his treatment of Eva Smith highlights how he is a selfish character.** . When Inspector Goole questions his assault of Eva Smith, Eric describes her as a "good sport." Although it portrays Eva as fun and lighthearted during their interactions, **it ultimately highlights** Eric's **objectification** of women, as it is a misogynistic and reductive phrase. **Eric arguably presents the upper class exploitation of the lower class, seen through how Eric uses Eva solely for sexual gratification, like how Mr Birling only uses her to become wealthier, and fires her once she demands higher wages.**  In addition, Eric attempts to justify his behaviour, as he "was in that state where a chap easily turns nasty." Justifying his actions as what "chaps" (good-behaved men) would normally do is reductive, as he blames his behaviour on his drunkness and passes it off as a norm, **showing his lack of culpability and responsibility.**  In addition, the verb "nasty" is a complete understatement for his rape, highlighting Eric's lack of seriousness towards his actions.  Although society at the time would not view these actions as hugely controversial as sexual assault was not highly illegalized, it still highlights how Eric is very irresponsible and entitled.

However, Eric presents inherit morality seen during Act 1, which contrasts his father and thus **foreshadows his redemption**. In his stage description his "half shy, half assertiveness" hints at his hidden darkness, but also suggests his hope and change as he has no ideals and thus no allegiance towards any viewpoint. In addition, he shows his morality as he questions his father Mr Birling, asking him "Why shouldn't they try for higher wages? We try for the highest possible prices," suggesting his socialist leanings**.The parallel structure highlights Eric‚Äôs beliefs of social equality and equal pay rights, and in addition to the rhetorical question suggesting how Eric is willing to fight for morality and overall more socialist beliefs, mirroring the Inspector‚Äôs rhetorical questions against the Birlings as the play progresses**. It also presents how Eric sees the potential for growth within the working class and treats them fairly, contrasting the redundant viewpoint of his parents, namely his father, with "keeping labour costs down" and being preocupied with one's own benefit alone. 

This changes however, as Eric is presented as somewhat redeemble as he attempts to refund money. Eric returns to find Eva and "insisted on giving her enough money to keep her going," suggesting how Eric feels guilt and is trying to recuperate the damage he had caused. This is made more clear as he steals "about fifty pounds" from Mr Birling, knowing that Mr Birling would not help him if he asked personally. This highlights Eric's sense of morality as he realises that he needs to compensate for his actions, but also shows the contrast between him and Mr Birling as Eric treats the lower-class respectfully whereas Mr Birling simply views them as disposable labour.

Mrs Birling \~50 min  
How is Mrs Birling presented in An Inspector Calls?  
Also analyse the language, structure and form in your answer.  
(30)

Mrs Birling is the mother of the Birling family, and clearly has a powerful role in the decisions made by Mr Birling and her children. She is presented as a cold and plain woman with a higher social class and status, and as a result she is one of the main proponents of capitalism. With her potent maintenence of the social status systems of 1912, it results in her being one of the least likeable members of the Birling household.

Mrs Birling is presented to uphold the patriarchy and the gender norms of the time, in addition to seeing marriages as contructs. She recognises that marriage is a way to secure financial security and social status, and that loyalty and trust are not seen as important. This is seen through her indifference to Gerald's affair and potentially Mr Birling's affair. Notably, she is also very indifferent about Eric's sexual assault of Eva Smith, except for when money is involved, as she says she is "very dissapointed" with Eric when finding out. Mrs Birling also understands Gerald's affair very early on, defending him from Sheila by saying that "men with important work to do sometimes have to spend nearly all their time and energy on their buisness." By only including "men" we see how Mrs BIrling believes that men are more productive and accepts the dominant role of men within society, reflecting her intergration within the patriarchal society. As she leaves the scene during Act 1, she ultimately echoes this sentiment as she initiates the women's exit as she announces it is time to "leave you men" in the drawing room, as men during the time often discussed buisness matters separately from the women, highlighting how Mrs BIrling continues to maintain the gender norms of the time without prompt.

In addition, Mrs Birling faithfully upholds the class system, displaying her ruthlessness as she patronises and is prejudice towards the lower class, selfishly focusing on her own status. This is hinted at during her stage directions, described as "rather cold," suggesting how she shows little emotion and is self-interested. We see how this manifests in her displayal of superiority towards the lower-class as she scrutinizes Eva Smith for sharing her last name, and defining that it was "one of the things that prejudiced \[Mrs Birling\] against her case." Unlike the younger generation, she shows no remorse for having shut down the request for economic aid, which deeply contrasts the ethics of the charity she runs. It implies that Mrs Birling joined the charity for her own status. In addition, she also critiques Eva Smith based off of her own class, as Mrs Birling says Eva is "giving herself ridiculous airs...claiming fine elaborate feelings..that were simpl absurd for a girl in her position." Ironically, the only one with "airs" is her, as she cannot see the emotional impact of Eva's suicide nor come to terms with accepting her own role in her death. In addition to this, she is ironically the only one who seems to be incapable of the depth of thought or emotion she describes the lower-class to lack. It is finally important to mention how she does not even view the lower-class as individuals, as she potently mentions her as "girls of that class," the strong determiner "that" showing how Mrs Birling collectifies and stereotypes the lower-class into a simple, inferior group of people who were not skilled enough to escape from their own class division. Resultingly, she garners dislike from the audience and the Inspector alike as he "sternly" interrogates her.

Finally, Mrs Birling is definingly presented as unchanging towards her own beliefs, resulting in her continual pushing of responsibility and blame to others. Luckily, her denial of responsibility initially condemns Eric as she blames Eric with "full responsibility," as she is unknowing to Eric's involvement in Eva's pregnancy. She is "(very distressed)" and says "There must be some mistake," which shows how her rigid class views are flawed as she is unable to fathom how her own son of middle-upper class had commited the crime. Yet, she quickly switches to critique him, as she "(comes to life)" and says "I'm absolutely ashamed of you" when Eric steals 50 pounds off of Mr Birling.  Mrs Birling seeks and upholds the capitalist, selfish mindset akin to Mr Birling, highlighting her resistance to the Inspector's socialist ideals. In addition, Mrs Birling maintains her capitalist viewpoints as she believes that the consequences of her actions are more important than the actions themselves, as she says "he certainly didn't make me confess \- I had done my duty." The definitive tone highlights how she believes   her status and position justifies her immoral actions, and thus have nothing to "confess" to. However, the hyphen suggests her uncertainty about her own morals, in which she then justifies and resolves that it was "her duty," maintaining her static, unempathetic stance towards Eva Smith. Finally, she also critiques the Inspector as she refuses to accept responsibility, using her status to critique the Inspector's behaviour, as she says "that \- I consider \- is a trifle impertinent, Inspector." The embedded clause "I consider" emphasises her pompousness (akin to Mr Birling), showing how Mrs Birling attempts to use her upper-class as a means to get the Inspector to show deference, and avoid questioning.

Mrs Birling is therefore used by Priestley to teach the audience of the dangers of hypocrisy, ignorance and capitalism. By pioritising her reputation over her morals or the growth of her family, and undoing the Inspector's message, she condemns herself and her family to being trapped in the cyclical punishment of the Inspector, indicated by the second Inspector that "calls" by the end of the play. Priestley uses Mrs Birling to teach the audience that in spiet of gender, maternal instincts or charitable titles, the upper class will always protect themselves above all else.

The Inspector 50 min  
How is the Inspector presented in An Inspector Calls?  
You must refer to the language, structure and form within your answer.  
(30) mid paragraph kind of mid, but last paragraph pretty good

Ostensibly, the Inspector is presented as powerful and important character. His purpose is outlined in the title of the play, "An Inspector Calls," as he swiftly begins "cutting in," and interrogating the Birling family (and Gerald Croft) about the murder of Eva Smith. However, as the play develops, it is clear that his uncanny knowledge about the family, his speech, and his sudden disappearance indicate his purpose to be beyond the events of Eva Smith's death itself, and instead as a warning against capitalism.

The Inspector is initially presented as a disruptive and powerful force, overriding the older Birling's percieved authority and status. Seen through the "sharp" ringing of the doorbell, highlighting the Inspector's irruptive entrance as he butts in, and metaphorically pops the bubble of the Birling family. This is further reinforced with the lighting changing from "pink and intimate" to "brighter and harder" upon the Inspector's arrival, emblematic of his metaphorical function of shining a light and revealing the deeds of the family (and Gerald Croft). His powerful stature is immediately highlighted through his stage description, as he "creates at once an impression of "massiveness, solidity and purposefulness," the word "solidity" suggestion how he is unmoveable, and immune to the wealth, status or intimidation of the Birlings. The Inspector maintains order and control even through his multi-interrogations as he "imposes himself between them and the photograph," physically taking control of the investigation, and placing his body between the photograph of Eva Smith and the higher class men. Perhaps it may also symbolise how he protects and defends the lower-class from the Birling family. We can see Mr Birling's frustrations as he attempts to intimidate the Inspector, saying "I ought to warn you that he's an old friend of mine...we play golf together," yet the Inspector simply replies "(dryly) I don't play golf." THe simple and flippant comment highlights the power the Inspector wields, as a voice of the common people, as he is willing to stand against those who believe their position gives them special treatment. 

In addition, the Inspector is presented as a quasi-supernatural figure, with an uncanny knowledge about the family. This is seen through the obvious pun of his name, being a "ghoul," playing on the idea of how he appears to be a supernatural being, haunting the Birling family. In addition, his uncanny knowledge of every aspect of the events which resulted in the tragic death of Eva Smith set him up as something more than a natural police Inspector. Only Sheila understands the Inspector's near omniscience as she says "He knows. Of course he knows." Yet, it is the very ending of the play that is the most strange, as the Inspector is found to not be a member of the Brumley police force. Crucially, only Eric and Sheila, the younger generation, realise his significance: Sheila says "what's important" is "not whether a man is a police inspector or not" but what they did to Eva Smith, likewise, Eric says "he was our police inspector all right." In addition, Sheila says he was "frightening," and that "he inspected us all right," the adjective "frightening" reflective of how powerful the Inspector was, as he seemingly scares the Birling family and collapsing the jovial mood upon his exit during Act 3\.

As his presence is dominating and his knowledge near-omniscient, he is thus used as Priestley's clear and evident mouthpiece in the play. After showing how each of the Birlings and Gerald are implicated in Eva Smith's suicide, the Inspector ends with a final speech, saying "There are millions and millions and millions of Eva Smiths and John Smiths left with us, their hopes and fears, their suffering and chance of happiness, all intertwined with our lives. The repetition of "millions" is used to highlight the sheer quantity of people oppressed by the cruel middle-upper class demonstrated by the Birlings and Gerald, lending sympathy towards the lower, working class. This is reinforced by the commonality of the last name "Smith" and common first names "Eva" and "John," symbollically using their names as a referal to the working class society as a whole. It is interesting how the Inspector displays their feelings, as "suffering" and with "happiness," almost as to suggest how they are real people with "lives" and emotions and thus are not understood like so and mistreated by the upper echilon of society. Perhaps Priestley is suggesting that the lower and upper class should treat each other fairly and equally, with the adjective "intertwined"  presenting lives of the rich and poor as conjunct and permamently connected. In contrast, the Inspector uses apocalyptic imagery as well, saying "If men will not learn that lesson, then they will be taught it in blood and fire and anguish." This would be a very emotive and evocative message, given the obvious reference to the two world wars, yet what is quite subversive about Priestley's message here is the suggestion that the violence and horror of the wars was somehow linked to the selfishness and a lack of empathy of individuals, the antithesis of Priestley‚Äôs message. He reinforces this with the declaratives "We don't live alone. We are members of one body. We are responsible for each other." The anaphora "We" and the tricolon draw attention of the audience, as an emphatic conclusion. With the metaphor "members of one body" he suggests that like limbs of a body, we cannot survive without each other, again emphasising the socialist idea that we must look out for the most vulnerable in society. Yet, the older Birlings do not understand nor take in the message, and are thus shocked by the cyclical, final ring of the telephone (of a second inspector) before the curtain fall. As the old Birlings and Gerald do not change their capitalist views, they are subjugated to the final punishment of the Inspector, perhaps alluding to Priestley's belief of capitalism as a root cause of the first or second world war.

Overall, Priestley presents the Inspector as a powerful voice for the lower-class, and his purpose as the near-supernatural surrogate author for Priestley's socialist and equilitarian views.

Overview  
Written in 1606 and set in 11th Scotland.  
The famous Shakespearean tragedy, dramatising the damaging physical and psychological effects of political ambition on those who seek power.

## **Context** {#context-1}

After analysis, discuss the effect on the audience. **Given the Jacobean audience were \[contextual facts\], it would have caused the audience to \[effect from Shakespeare\]. This further enhances the \[topic point\].**

Ex. witches  
Given the Jacobean audience were tabooed from being connected with witchcraft, particularly due to the increasing witch hunts and executions following King James I‚Äôs accession, they would have naturally treated the witches introduction seriously and would have feared the effects they would have on the tragic hero Macbeth. Shakespeare therefore uses the witches and the supernatural to warn against correlating with the supernatural as it only leads to disaster and corrupt deeds ‚Äì perhaps most fearful of all, the suggestion that even noble and logical characters such as Macbeth can be manipulated and controlled by the supernatural, and thus his downfall serving as a warning from Shakespeare against those who thought about treason, which would have been very evocative considering the political unrest from King James‚Äô reign over two countries and the Gunpowder plot which had only occurred a year before the play was written.

### **‚ÄúFair is foul and foul is fair‚Äù** {#‚Äúfair-is-foul-and-foul-is-fair‚Äù}

Themes: Appearance and reality, supernatural  
Characters: The Witches‚Äô power, Macbeth‚Äôs fate?

- The **chiasmus/paradox** between ‚Äúfair and foul‚Äù presents the theme of reversal.  
- The witches would seem morally ambivalent to a modern audience.  
- A Jacobean audience would notice their malice instead, as they believed in the *Great Chain of Being.* The witches disrupt the natural order, and thus were seen as evil.  
- The **troachic tetrameter** contrasted the moral characters who spoke in blank verse, symbolising the witches‚Äô evil.  
- The chant-like and **falling meter** represents the moral corruption of Macbeth and Scotland.  
- Perhaps the caesura represents the witches unnatural views.  
- The witches would appeal to King James, as he believed in superstition, and wrote the book Daemonologie.  
- The witches would be evil to all audiences, as they are going against the conventional values of good and bad.

### **‚ÄúLook like the innocent flower, but be the serpent under‚Äôt** {#‚Äúlook-like-the-innocent-flower,-but-be-the-serpent-under‚Äôt}

- The **imperative** shows Lady Macbeth‚Äôs dominance and subversion of gender roles.  
- This would be a sign of corruption as women were expected to be subservient to their husbands.  
- ‚ÄúLook like‚Äù encourages Macbeth to be duplicious to hide his evil intentions.

### **Ambition and Power** {#ambition-and-power}

Macbeth is a play about ambition and its consequences. It can also be seen as a warning against those who seek to undermine or overthrow the rule of a rightful king.

#### **Macbeth as a tragedy** {#macbeth-as-a-tragedy}

Knowledge and evidence:

- The play is in the form of a tragedy, and thus has a tragic hero as its protagonist, Macbeth  
- Thus, Macbeth must have a tragic flaw, the harmtia  
- Often this was hubris, confidence in your ambitions  
- Macbeth parallels Ancient Greek tragedies in the fact that his harmatia is ambition.  
- Tragic flaws led to punishment and death, which is what Macbeth recieves  
- Shakespeare punishes Macbeth in a Christian context (reflecting the largely Christian Jacobean society)  
- Macbeth abandons his morals ‚Äì at first, he is initially presented as a noble and loyal general ‚Äì in his pursuit of, and his attempt to cling on to, power.  
- The character of Macbeth is corrupted by his ambition, which leads him to commit regicide (‚ÄúI have no spur to prick on the sides of my intent‚Ä¶‚Äù), the murder of his best friend (Banquo; ‚Äúif it find heaven, must find it out tonight‚Äù) and the murder of Macduff‚Äôs women and children. For this he is condemned to death at the hands of Macduff, but also to hell by God.  
- Shakespeare also presents Lady Macbeth as ambitious, and her punishment is equally severe but far less noble, as she commits suicide.

Shakespeare‚Äôs intention:

- Shakespeare is presenting a morality play to his Jacobean audience: allow yourself to be morally corrupted and act against societal norms, and you will suffer the consequences.

#### **Kingship and the Divine Right of Kings** {#kingship-and-the-divine-right-of-kings}

Knowledge and evidence:

- The Jacobean audience believed in the Divine Right of Kings.  
- Macbeth committing treason, regicide, was therefore an act against God  
- A Christian audience would have understood regicide as a mortal sin. This meant dying without the grace of God and being condemned to Hell, a terrifying prospect for any Jacobean.   
- \*Macbeth demonstrates this by being unable to say ‚ÄúAmen,‚Äù hearing voices that he has ‚Äúmurder\[ed\] sleep,‚Äù and overall being unsettled, with incoherent stichomythia with his wife.  
- In the play, Duncan is referred to as a ‚Äúking‚Äù, whereas Macbeth is referred to as a ‚Äútyrant‚Äù  
- Kings were seen to bring harmony to their kingdom, and tyrants only chaos and disorder. Shakespeare shows this clearly to please King James (for flattery)  
- The play ends with Malcom becoming king, restoring order as Duncan‚Äôs son and true heir. Functions as denounment and catharsis for audience.

Shakespeare‚Äôs intention

- Shakespeare is upholding contemporary views about kingship  
- He is suggesting that people who are unnaccustomed and undeserving of power will destroy and be destroyed by it.  
- Shakespeare suggests that Kings are legitimate rulers, but tyrants are not. (Gunpowder plot)

### **The Supernatural** {#the-supernatural}

Most people in Jacobean England were Christian. Therefore, supernatural events were seen as the evil work of the devil.

Knowledge and evidence:

- There was still a widespread belief in witchcraft  
- Witches were seen as agents of Satan, and many women wer eexecuted on baseless accusations of being witches  
- Jacobean audiences and \*King James I were fascinated by the presentation of witches, and naturally distrusted them.   
- \*Evidenced by his book, *Daemonologie*  
- The witches in Macbeth are therefore seen as untrustworthy and malevolent.  
- The first scene involves an ominous setting (‚Äúin thunder, lightning, or in rain‚Äù,) and three witches, silencing the audience and foreshadowing future acts.  
- The witches are also shown to be capable of affecting the weather, creating spells and committing evil acts against ordinary people.  
- Macbeth should know better, but his ambition means he trusts the witches  
- Banquo ‚Äì who represents societal norms, and \*being King James I‚Äôs supposed ancestor ‚Äì rightly does not trust the witches.  
- \*Banquo originally works with Macbeth to kill King Duncan, but Shakespeare altered the base material Holinshed Chronicles as it would be unwise to suggest King Duncan‚Äôs ancestor as a cospirer of evil and supernatural.  
- The witches are seen as disruptive characters, negatively influencing Macbeth and misleading him with their prophecies.  
* ‚Äúshalt be King hereafter‚Äù ‚ÄúNo man of woman born shall harm Macbeth‚Äù (leading to his overconfidence and downfall)  
* The supernatural also acts as an aid to characters, wishing to gain, or retain, power:  
- Lady Macbeth calls on evil spirits to help her achieve her ambitions (Act I, Scene V)  
- Macbeth returns to the witches a second time (Act IV, Scene I)

Shakespeare‚Äôs intention:

- Shakespeare suggests that the witches are a symbol of all temptations that humans have to wrestle with.  
- Alternatively, they can be seen as agents of fate: they just encourage Macbeth to act upon his true nature.

### **Appearance vs Reality** {#appearance-vs-reality}

Shakespeare presents the theme of perception throughout Macbeth: are we seeing what‚Äôs really there? 

#### **Hallucinations** {#hallucinations}

Knowledge and evidence:

- Macbeth sees visions or hears things throughout the play  
  - bloody dagger  
  - knocking  
  - A voice telling him he‚Äôs murdered sleep  
  - Banquo‚Äôs ghost  
- Lady Macbeth also has visions of blood on her hands (V.i)  
- All hallucinations are representations of guilt  
- Macbeth feels conflicted before murdering Duncan, seeing the bloody dagger before he commits regicide.  
- The repeated knocking and voice telling Macbeth he‚Äôs murdered sleep represent the lack of peace the character will experience from then on.  
- Even Lady Macbeth, who resolved to kill Duncan, eventually sees visions of blood on her hands, a metaphor for her guilt and responsibility for his murder.

Shakespeare‚Äôs intention:

- It is unclear if Shakespeare intended for the visions to be real, yet it is clear that they represent psychological realities for both Macbeth and Lady Macbeth.  
- Shakespeare thus presents guilt, and divine retribution as inescapable.

#### **Duplicitous characters** {#duplicitous-characters}

Deception is a repeated motif throughout the play.

Knowledge and evidence:

- The witches constantly mislead Macbeth: although all their prophecies do come true, they are deliberately worded to deceive Macbeth  
- Traitors and treason are repeatedly mentioned throughout the play:  
  - Macbeth kills a **traitor** in battle  
  - The former Thane of Cawdor was a traitor  
  - Macduff is wrongly accused of being a traitor  
- These are all ironic references from Shakespeare since the principal traitor is Macbeth, who:

  - then becomes a treasonous Thane  
  - ultimately killed by the loyal Macduff  
- Lady Macbeth encourages Macbeth to be duplicitous:

- Macbeth lies to Banquo, his best friend  
  - Macbeth claims to not think about the witches  
  - Aims to find out where to send the assassins  
- Macbeth even keeps truths from Lady Macbeth (III,ii), showing the breakdown of their once-close relationship.

Shakespeare‚Äôs intention:

- Shakespeare suggests that those who deceive and lie will not prosper  
- He suggests that those who lie or use violence will end up in a cycle of more deceit and violence.

#### **Swapping gender roles** {#swapping-gender-roles}

Knowledge and evidence:

- Lady Macbeth calls on evils spirits to give her ‚Äòmasculine‚Äô characteristics as she wishes to be ‚Äúcruel‚Äù (I.v)  
- LM wishes to remove traits that are stereotypically feminine at the time, such as being motherly and having remorse.  
- She then describes Macbeth in feminine terms, having ‚Äútoo full of the milk of human kindness‚Äù   
- And finally questions Macbeth‚Äôs masculinity when he is having doubts about killing Duncan  
  - ‚ÄúWhen you durst do it, then you were a man‚Äù

  - ‚ÄúAnd yet your beards forbid me to interpret..‚Äù (I.iii)

Shakespeare‚Äôs intention:

- Shakespeare presents an atypical relationship where Lady Macbeth wields more power than Macbeth (initially.)  
- Jacobean audiences would have found this power dynamic disturbing and unnatural.  
- Shakespeare suggests that feminine power is bound to end in tragedy, conforming to the conservative Jacobean belief that the subversion of gender roles leads to disaster.  
- A progressive viewpoint is showing the tragedy of a patriarchal society, as he shows the consequences of limiting women‚Äôs agencies.

Jacobean audiences believed the world heeded [*God‚Äôs plan.*](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XUqRem0W8L8) Any disruption to the world was therefore a disruption to God‚Äôs orders.

### **Attempts** {#attempts-2}

How is Macbeth presented in the play Macbeth?  
You must consider the structure, language, and form within your answer.   
(30)

Macbeth is the tragic hero of the play Macbeth, and thus, Shakespeare must characterise him with heroism, harmatia, sympathy, and his subsequent downfall. Macbeth is initially presented as heroic and noble, yet succumbs to his harmatia: ambition. He kills King Duncan, Banquo, and causes chaos as the new king. However, he is presented with sympathy as he is shown to be influenced by the Witches and Lady Macbeth, who spur him on to commit his horrible sins. Resultingly, he must die at the end of the play, to restore the natural order and give the audience a sense of catharsis from the chaos he creates.

At the beginning of the play,  Macbeth is presented as brave, and noble, where his consientous governs over his ambition, presenting him as moral and heroic.  
His fearlessness is highlighted as he proves himself to be a skilled warrior; King Duncan and his messengers personify him as an "eagle" and a "lion," (I.ii) showing his prowess in battle, akin to a predator. He is characterised by his nobility,  as he kills the traitor Macdonwald, showing his loyalty to the king, as he skillfully "unseamed him from the nave to the chops." The verb "unseamed" is an act of sewing, which highlights the precise and masterful skill Macbeth has in battle. He is clearly presented as a brave and worthy soldier, commended by the King as a "worthy cousin," and is given the title of the Thane of Cawdor for his efforts. 

Macbeth is also initially presented as such within the next scene (I.iii), as he viscerally reacts to the thought of regicide, highlighting his consientousness in spite of his ambition or the Witches' prophecies. Macbeth has his "heart knock against \[his\] ribs," upon thinking about regicide, which would present him as virtuous and moral for the christian, Jacobean audience \- such an act would be defying the Great Chain of Being, which would have been the worst act against God.  A *The* physical reaction from Macbeth thus highlights his initial morality as he deems *feels* the defiance of natural order is harmful.

However, as the play progresses, Macbeth is presented as a much less sympathetic character, as he chooses to murder Duncan, violating the Great Chain of Being. Even after becoming king, he becomes even more cruel and violent, succumbing to his ambition *‚Äì as* Macbeth orders the murders of his best friend Banquo, Macduff's wife and children, all in his attempt to retain his power and obtain a legacy. Macbeth comments on how "to be thus is nothing, but to be safely thus." (III.i) highlighting his insecurity and disatisfaction with being King now, as it is "nothing," showing Macbeth's engulfing ambition and selfishness. In addition, he chooses to fight against the Witches' prophecies, and perhaps God's retribution, as he says "come Fate into the list, and champion me to the utterance." The personification of Fate and the metaphorical duel he challenges, reflects his increasingly violent nature as he now uses violence to maintain his power as King. From another perspective, "Fate" could also be God's condemning of Macbeth as he violates the natural order and has killed the king, which would have been beyond horrifying for Jacobean audiences as Macbeth now acclaims to challenge the authority of God himself. 

Yet, possible sympathy is generated for Macbeth as the audience is given insights into his guilt, paranoia and nihilistic views, *fufilling* the role of a tragic hero. Macbeth experiences many hallucinations, representing his feelings of guilt towards the regicide and the murder of Banquo. Macbeth *rhetorically* questions "will all great Neptune's ocean wash this blood clean from my hands?" (II.ii) turning to a Roman god as he believes he is condemned and rejected by Christianity for his deeds. The modal verb "will" and the question also highlights his plea as he feels like the blood (and metaphorically, his deeds and guilt) cannot be washed away.  His guilt for Banquo is similarly expressed as he is horrified by the ghost of Banquo, a manifestation of his guilt. He exclaims "never shake thy gory locks at me\!" (III,iv), with the "gory locks" representing Banquo's bloody hair, and the violent murder that took place. With no one else in the scene being able to 'see' the ghost of Banquo, with the exception of the audience, Shakespeare suggests that Macbeth's guilt is a form of divine consequence of murder and violence. This ultimately leads Macbeth to paranoia: he begins to stop sharing *his plans* with Lady Macbeth, and exclaims how "full of scorpions is my mind." The metaphor highlights how Macbeth's mind is deteriorating and is being weighed by guilt, as his evil deeds (represented by the scorpions) metaphorically sting and pollute his mind, akin to toxins, highlighting how Macbeth is ultimately suffering as a result of his guilt. Finally, with the exceeding guilt and paranoia, Macbeth's mental deterioration is shown as he becomes nihilistic. Upon hearing of Lady Macbeth's death, he says how "she should've died hereafter." (V.v), the *short phrase* highlighting the lack of concern highlighting Macbeth's callousness, in spite of a lover's death which should have been emotional and tragic.  In addition, he has a lengthy soliloquy, saying "Out, out, brief candle\!" Using the "brief candle" as a metaphor for his life highlights how little importance he believes his life to be \- with the repetition of "out," he ultimately recognises his death to be imminent. His self-referral as an "idiot," and his actions as a act on a "stage," serve to highlight his actions as meaningless, a complete antithesis of Christian beliefs of meanings in life and morals. Shakespeare is presenting Macbeth as a man who has become so ridden with guilt and detached from Christianity that he has no meaning in life nor can feel anything, not even the death of his loved ones. The audience is made to feel sympathy for Macbeth, as he suffers and ultimately mentally deteriorates as a result of his deeds.

Audiences may also feel sympathy as Macbeth's ambition to kill the king can be viewed as fueled by the Witches and Lady Macbeth, who are both unnatural. The witches are clearly presented as the malevolent evil; for the Jacobean audiences, their entrance in Act I will cause silence and discord as they are seen as the servants of Satan, and caused disruption to the natural order.  *This is* reflected *as* they intentionally go "there to meet with Macbeth," mentioning Macbeth before his first appearance. Shakespeare presents the witches as the initial propagator for Macbeth's ambition *and tragedy,* spurring him on to his downfall. Lady Macbeth, as well, encourages Macbeth to commit the regicide, and she describes how Macbeth is "too full of the milk of human kindness." She subverts gender roles, being the dominate in their marriage, *seen through how she* emasculates Macbeth, metaphorically presenting him as somewhat feminine as he has too much "kindness," as gender roles during the Jacobean era dictated that women were more gentle and kind than men.  She also manipulates Macbeth by preying along Macbeth's desire to be masculine: as he "dare\[s\] do all that may become a man,‚Äù subsequently taunting him, saying ‚ÄúWhen you durst do it, then you were a man.‚Äù Lady Macbeth associates achieving personal ambition with bravery and masculinity, repeating ‚Äúyou‚Äù whilst asking many rhetorical questions to manipulate Macbeth into commiting the regicide. With Lady Macbeth initially appearing alone in the scene, and her subsequent plan to have Macbeth murder Duncan, audiences are made to subsequently believe that Lady Macbeth propagates Macbeth to commit the regicide. Although Macbeth ultimately chooses to kill Duncan himself, it is clear that it may have failed without the Witches prophecies nor Lady Macbeth's manipulation.

Overall, Macbeth is presented as a complex character in the play. As the tragic hero, he is doomed to die due to his harmatia, excessive ambition, yet Shakespeare demonstrates how human Macbeth is through his moral consiousness and his following guilt. Even his death is heroic (for the Jacobeans) as he dies a warrior's death, with "harness on \[his\] back." Shakespeare therefore uses Macbeth to warn of the allure of ambition and how corrupting it can be, as it causes even the initially noble and moral Macbeth his life, his sanity, and the lives of those around him.
